1. HTTP Methods (HTTP Verbs)
HTTP methods indicate the intended action to be performed on a resource, corresponding to CRUD operations:

Method	   Operation	                      Description	                                        Example
GET	         Read	                   Retrieves data from the server without modifying it.	    Fetching a list of patients
POST	     Create	                  Submits data to create a new resource in the database.    Adding a new patient
PUT	         Update	                  Updates and completely replaces an existing resource. 	Updating all details of a patient
PATCH	     Update	                  Performs a partial update on an existing resource.	    Updating only a patient's phone number
DELETE	     Delete	                  Removes a specific resource from the database.	        Deleting a patient record



2. HTTP Status Codes
Status codes express the result of the request sent by the client to the backend. They are categorized into 5 standard classes:

A. Success (2xx)
200 OK: The request succeeded and data was returned (commonly used with GET, PUT, PATCH).

201 Created: The request succeeded and a new resource was successfully created (used with POST).

204 No Content: The request succeeded, but there is no content to return in the response body (commonly used with DELETE).

B. Client Errors (4xx)
400 Bad Request: The request payload is malformed, invalid, or missing required fields.

401 Unauthorized: Authentication is required (the user needs to log in first).

403 Forbidden: The server understands the request, but the user lacks the required permissions.

404 Not Found: The requested resource or URL endpoint does not exist.

C. Server Errors (5xx)
500 Internal Server Error: An unexpected error occurred on the server side (e.g., code crash or bug).

503 Service Unavailable: The server is temporarily unable to handle the request (e.g., maintenance or overload).